EXECUTIVE SUMMARY

ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE POLICIES
Avon Products' (Avon) Zanesville facility is a state-of-the-art distribution center that handles 50% of Avon's U.S. distribution when fully operational.  The Zanesville facility employes 535 people when fully operational.  The site has one (1) covered process, Program Level 1, Aerosol Product Flammable Mixture Storage, that is subject to chemical accident prevention regulations under Section 112(r) of the Clean Air Act and 40 Code of Federal Regulations (CFR) part 68.  The covered process has no public receptors within the distance to the endpoint (0.2 miles or 1,056 feet) from a worst-case release and has had no accidents with specific off-site consequences within the past five years.
Avon's Global Safety Strategy has six (6) dimensions:
1.	Increase management involvement;
2.	Strengthen basic safety;
3.	Set goals and measure performance;
4.	Communicate and increase awareness;
5.	Increase safety and health competence; and
6.	Establish global standards.

Associates responsible for coordinating health and safety management report directly to the facility's Local Crisis Management Team (CMT Leader, Global Security Designee, Human Resources, Legal, Communications, Finance, Facilities, IT, Security, and EHS); the North American Regional Crisis Management Team (SVP & President NA, VP Finance, GVP NA Legal, VP Communications and Events, Executive Director IT, and VP HR NA); and the Global Crisis Management Team (CFO/Chief Strategy Officer, SVP General Counsel, SVP Global Communications, and SVP Human Resources).   By assigning health and safety responsibilities to the associates who are directly involved in the facility's operational areas and reporting directly to senior (local, regional, and global) management, the safety function becomes more effective and sends a clear message that ensuring safety is a basic management function and responsibility.  
